The most significant event that happened to Northern Cyprus in the past 20 years is the Action Plan approved by the European Commission in 1999 for the accession of the country to the EU. The action plan included extensive agreements to be undertaken by the Turkish Cypriot side, including the preparation of the necessary legislation on human rights and the distribution of competencies with the participation of the Greek Cypriot side.

In the pre EU era Turkey did very little in terms of development projects in Cyprus, by applying instead a so called national-development policy, resembling the revisionist policy applied in the early years of state- building.^1 Turkey took over the whole territory of Cyprus after the military intervention of July 20, 1974 and applied a policy that led to the regrets expressed by the Trustee Committee report (^2), member states were asking, instead of “Why Turkey should make Cyprus and its excluded part [Northern Cyprus] part of her sphere of influence” to ask why Ankara did not move the same way as Ankara tried to do with Cyprus in respect of Armenia, in order to achieve an official understanding.^3

The unilateral withdrawal of scheduled armies to the areas defined as military Zone A, after the release of Nakıba report and subsequent actions of the European Parliament (^4), brought a promise of change.
